        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>In Band 6, the flux of the MC27-MM1 and MM2 are measured 
to be about 2 and 1 mJy/beam in 1" spacial resolution observation, respectively. 
The expected flux of the source will be roughly 
5- and 2.5 mJy/beam at 350GHz for MM1 and MM2, respectively. 
The sum of the area of MM1 and MM2 is around 2 arcsec^2, 
which roughly corresponds to 7 times of the beam size of Band 7.  
If the emission is distributed equally in the area, we expect to detect 
roughly 1 mJy per beam.  

Assuming the inclination angle 
of 60 degrees for the outflow axis, we expect to detect 8% or above 
of linear polarization degrees if the continuum sources are in 
before First Core phase or right after the second collapse occur, 
based on the study by Kataoka et al. 2012. 
8 % of 1mJy corresponds to 0.08 mJy.  The desired sensitivity 
per pointing that we request is 0.02 mJy.  For this case, 
we can detect the polarized signal with 4 sigma or above of significance.   

If the source is in the evolved Second core phase, the polarization 
degree is likely to be approximately 2 %. 
For this case, we may not be able to detect significant polarized 
signal.  However, it still gives us important information
about the evolutionary status of the oject.  

Depending on how much polarization degrees we detect, 
we can put a strong constrain on their evolutionary phases. 

</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
